ave played everquest for almost 2 years now, and the whole concept of what a guild means to me has changed throughout.  In the beginning, i had no idea why i was being invited into the "fellowship of fire", but it sounded cool, and once I had joined (gladstone), I had a whole new aspect of the game open up for me.  I started finding out where to group, what sites to visit, what skills were important, what classes could do... it was informational.<br>
<br>
a few months later the guild halls were empty and lacking people to group with, I found "sacred legions" a middle tier guild where everyone gained from grouping and leveling together.  I spent my 20-40 levels in sacred legions before that guild went the way of the dodo, and was recruited into "Storm legions".  This was my first access to kael, and some of the higher end zones.  I would see sebilis, chardok, and had the resources to explore most zones in the game with a guild group.  I attended my first raids, and learned alot from the raid leaders.<br>
<br>
As most of those guilds, storm legion suffered, and still suffers from attrition at the top.  There is no shame in it, people leave to raid the upper end content, and for that they need a guild geared to doing that.  It is unfortunate for guilds like Storm Legions that our friends continue to leave and move to more favorable ground instead of sticking around to lift their friends to the top.  We are certainly not the only guild that experiences the problem.  I assume it is a flaw in the foundation that prevents those people from lifting the guild.<br>
<br>
What makes a guild special?  Is it the content you get to see, or the people you meet along the way?  For me it has always been about the people.  It is sad that the people equation invariably changes, and that you loose the bonds of the people who move to new guilds.  You are left to constantly rebuild again.  Content is obviously important as well, because people leave for exactly that reason.<br>
<br>
if I had to come up with a list of things that I think might make a guidl successful I would choose these:<br>
<br>
1) narrow band of level range.  55-60.  The reason for this is that people will not outlevel you, and no one in the guild channel would ever be too much of a drag on an exp group.  The only place this can work is at the top end of the level range.  This alone is probably why people are unable to ever lift their guilds to the top.<br>
<br>
2) timezone centric.  Recruit only players commited to a single timezone and window of playing.  This is to foster cameraderie between members.<br>
<br>
3) Class distribution.  Need to be balanced, but I don't know how you can ever really accmpolish this.  Should a guild ever be "full" for your class?  If that is the case, I would think you would deguild a person for lack of attendance?<br>
<br>
4) Raids - I think in the end this is the biggest reason to have a guild.  The alliance does a nice job of grouping multiple guilds together to raid, but organization is cumbersome and requires more lead time and planning.  <br>
<br>
5) Social - The second biggest reason is to see your friends when you log in.  Make sure that you help each other with epics, and other progression in the game.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that those rules do not favor the casual player.  When I look at guilds that have been successful for a while, I wonder if they have any casual players among them.  is it possible to make a successful longterm guild of casual players?  What do you think makes a guild successful?<br>
<br>
-gremli<br>
